{
  "Cancer is primarily caused by mutations in which two categories of genes?": "",
  "Proto-oncogenes (which become oncogenes) and tumor suppressor genes": "",
  "Histone genes and ribosomal genes": "",
  "tRNA genes and rRNA genes": "",
  "Mitochondrial genes and chloroplast genes": "",
  "Cancer typically arises from gain-of-function mutations in proto-oncogenes (creating oncogenes that promote cell growth) combined with loss-of-function mutations in tumor suppressor genes (removing growth brakes).": "",
  "Oncogenes promote cancer by:": "",
  "Producing proteins that constitutively stimulate cell growth and division": "",
  "Repairing DNA double-strand breaks": "",
  "Slowing the cell cycle to allow DNA repair": "",
  "Triggering apoptosis in damaged cells": "",
  "Oncogenes encode overactive or overexpressed proteins that drive uncontrolled cell proliferation. They can be mutant growth factors, receptors, signal transduction proteins, or transcription factors that are stuck in the 'on' position.": "",
  "The 'two-hit hypothesis' for tumor suppressor genes states that:": "",
  "A cell must be hit by two different carcinogens": "",
  "Both alleles of a tumor suppressor gene must be inactivated before the cell loses that tumor-suppressing function": "",
  "Two rounds of cell division must occur before a mutation becomes cancerous": "",
  "Two different oncogenes must be activated for cancer to develop": "",
  "Knudson's two-hit hypothesis explains that since tumor suppressors are recessive at the cellular level, both alleles must be inactivated for the cell to lose that growth-restraining function. One functional copy is usually sufficient to prevent uncontrolled growth.": "",
  "Which of the following is a hallmark of cancer cells?": "",
  "They can sustain proliferative signaling, evade growth suppressors, resist apoptosis, and induce angiogenesis": "",
  "They undergo apoptosis more readily than normal cells": "",
  "They respond normally to contact inhibition": "",
  "They have fewer mutations than normal cells": "",
  "The hallmarks of cancer include sustaining proliferative signaling, evading growth suppressors, resisting cell death, enabling replicative immortality, inducing angiogenesis, and activating invasion and metastasis.": "",
  "Angiogenesis in cancer refers to:": "",
  "The programmed death of cancer cells": "",
  "The ability of cancer cells to divide without growth factors": "",
  "The spread of cancer to distant organs": "",
  "The formation of new blood vessels that supply the tumor with oxygen and nutrients": "",
  "Tumors secrete signals (like VEGF) that stimulate the growth of new blood vessels toward the tumor. These vessels provide oxygen and nutrients needed for continued tumor growth and also serve as routes for metastasis.": "",
  "Carcinogens cause cancer by:": "",
  "Enhancing the immune system's ability to detect tumors": "",
  "Increasing the rate of apoptosis": "",
  "Causing DNA mutations that can activate oncogenes or inactivate tumor suppressor genes": "",
  "Directly killing all cells in the body": "",
  "Carcinogens (such as UV radiation, tobacco smoke, and certain chemicals) damage DNA, introducing mutations. When these mutations affect genes controlling cell growth, they can initiate the multi-step process leading to cancer.": "",
  "Tumor viruses (oncogenic viruses) can cause cancer by:": "",
  "Directly repairing mutations in host DNA": "",
  "Integrating viral oncogenes into the host genome or producing proteins that inactivate host tumor suppressors": "",
  "Preventing the host cell from dividing": "",
  "Increasing the host cell's ability to undergo apoptosis": "",
  "Oncogenic viruses (like HPV, Hepatitis B, and EBV) can cause cancer by integrating viral oncogenes, inactivating tumor suppressors (HPV's E6 protein degrades p53, E7 inactivates Rb), or causing chronic inflammation that promotes mutations.": "",
  "Cancer develops through a multi-step process because:": "",
  "Each cancer gene mutates in a specific predetermined order": "",
  "Multiple mutations must accumulate in genes controlling different aspects of cell growth, death, and invasion to overcome the cell's many safeguards": "",
  "Only one cell in the body can give rise to cancer": "",
  "A single mutation is always immediately lethal": "",
  "Cancer is a multi-step process requiring the accumulation of multiple mutations (typically 5-7) over years or decades. Each mutation provides a selective growth advantage, and the progressive accumulation of mutations transforms a normal cell into a malignant cancer cell.": "",
  "p53 prevents cancer development by:": "",
  "Halting the cell cycle when DNA damage is detected and triggering apoptosis if the damage cannot be repaired": "",
  "Increasing angiogenesis to improve nutrient supply to cells": "",
  "Promoting rapid cell division to replace damaged cells": "",
  "Activating oncogenes to compensate for tumor suppressor loss": "",
  "p53 is activated by DNA damage and induces expression of p21 (which arrests the cell cycle at G1) and pro-apoptotic genes (which trigger programmed cell death if damage is irreparable). Loss of p53 removes this critical checkpoint.": "",
  "Benign tumors differ from malignant tumors in that benign tumors:": "",
  "Grow uncontrollably and spread to other parts of the body": "",
  "Contain more mutations than malignant tumors": "",
  "Remain localized and do not invade surrounding tissues or metastasize": "",
  "Are always caused by viral infections": "",
  "Benign tumors grow in a localized area, are often encapsulated, and do not invade nearby tissues or metastasize. Malignant tumors are invasive, can break through tissue boundaries, and have the ability to spread to distant sites through the blood or lymph.": "",
  "What is an 'oncogene'?": "",
  "A normal gene that prevents cancer by suppressing cell growth": "",
  "A gene that causes cells to undergo apoptosis": "",
  "A mutated or overexpressed version of a proto-oncogene that promotes uncontrolled cell growth and can contribute to cancer development": "",
  "A viral gene that has no role in cancer": "",
  "An oncogene is a mutant version of a normal proto-oncogene. The mutation causes the encoded protein to be overactive or overproduced, driving excessive cell proliferation. Oncogenes act dominantly: a single mutant allele is sufficient to promote cancer.": "",
  "What does 'carcinogen' mean?": "",
  "Any physical, chemical, or biological agent that can cause cancer by inducing DNA mutations or promoting tumor growth": "",
  "An enzyme that repairs cancer-causing mutations": "",
  "A protein produced by cancer cells to evade the immune system": "",
  "A type of cancer cell that has metastasized": "",
  "A carcinogen is any substance or agent capable of causing cancer. Chemical carcinogens include tobacco smoke and asbestos, physical carcinogens include UV and ionizing radiation, and biological carcinogens include certain viruses (HPV, Hepatitis B).": "",
  "What is 'metastasis'?": "",
  "The growth of new blood vessels into a tumor under most circumstances involving cancer": "",
  "The programmed death of cancer cells, since the relevant cancer factors typically produce this outcome in practice": "",
  "The initial formation of a tumor at the primary site without accounting for additional influences": "",
  "The process by which cancer cells spread from the primary tumor to distant organs through the bloodstream or lymphatic system, establishing secondary tumors": "",
  "Metastasis is the spread of cancer cells from the original site to distant organs. Cancer cells must detach from the primary tumor, enter blood or lymph vessels, survive in circulation, exit at a distant site, and establish a new tumor. This is what makes cancer lethal.": "",
  "What does 'angiogenesis' mean?": "",
  "The formation of new blood vessels from pre-existing vasculature, which tumors stimulate to obtain oxygen and nutrients for growth": "",
  "The process of programmed cell death": "",
  "The genetic mutation that transforms a normal cell into a cancer cell": "",
  "The invasion of cancer cells into surrounding tissues": "",
  "Angiogenesis is the sprouting of new blood vessels from existing ones. Tumors larger than 1-2 mm require their own blood supply and secrete pro-angiogenic factors like VEGF to recruit new vessels. Anti-angiogenic drugs (like bevacizumab) target this process.": "",
  "What is the 'Warburg effect'?": "",
  "The observation that most cancer cells preferentially use glycolysis followed by lactic acid fermentation for energy, even in the presence of oxygen (aerobic glycolysis)": "",
  "The tendency of cancer cells to undergo apoptosis when oxygen is available": "",
  "Cancer cells using oxidative phosphorylation exclusively for energy": "",
  "The increased DNA repair rate in tumor cells": "",
  "The Warburg effect describes the metabolic shift in cancer cells toward aerobic glycolysis. Even with adequate oxygen, cancer cells ferment most glucose to lactate rather than fully oxidizing it. This provides biosynthetic intermediates for rapid growth, even though it is less energy-efficient.": "",
  "What is a 'tumor suppressor gene'?": "",
  "A gene found only in tumor cells, as the dynamics involved tend to push conditions in this direction over time": "",
  "A gene whose normal protein product restrains cell growth, promotes DNA repair, or triggers apoptosis; loss of function contributes to cancer": "",
  "A gene that, when activated by mutation, drives uncontrolled cell division": "",
  "A gene that encodes a growth factor, which represents a common but incomplete view of how these cell dynamics operate": "",
  "Tumor suppressor genes encode proteins that act as brakes on the cell cycle. Both alleles typically must be inactivated (two-hit hypothesis) for the cell to lose this protective function. Examples include TP53, RB1, BRCA1, and APC.": "",
  "What does 'malignant' mean in the context of tumors?": "",
  "A tumor caused exclusively by viral infection": "",
  "A cancerous tumor that is invasive, capable of spreading to other parts of the body, and potentially life-threatening": "",
  "A tumor that responds well to chemotherapy": "",
  "A tumor that is harmless and does not spread": "",
  "Malignant describes tumors that are cancerous: they invade surrounding tissues, can metastasize to distant organs, and are potentially fatal. This distinguishes them from benign tumors, which remain localized and are usually not life-threatening.": "",
  "What is a 'proto-oncogene'?": "",
  "A gene carried only by cancer-causing viruses": "",
  "A normal cellular gene that encodes a protein promoting cell growth and division, which can become an oncogene through mutation": "",
  "A gene that has already been mutated into an oncogene": "",
  "A gene that suppresses tumor formation": "",
  "Proto-oncogenes are normal genes essential for cell growth, proliferation, and differentiation. When mutated (point mutation, amplification, translocation), they become oncogenes that encode overactive proteins driving uncontrolled cell growth.": "",
  "What does 'benign tumor' mean?": "",
  "A tumor that arises only from viral infections": "",
  "A tumor that has begun to metastasize to other organs": "",
  "A cancerous growth that requires immediate surgery": "",
  "A mass of abnormal cells that remains localized, is often encapsulated, does not invade surrounding tissues, and does not metastasize": "",
  "Benign tumors are non-cancerous growths that do not invade nearby tissues or spread to distant sites. While they can sometimes cause problems by pressing on surrounding structures, they are generally not life-threatening and can often be surgically removed.": "",
  "What is the 'multi-hit model' of cancer?": "",
  "The concept that cancer arises from the progressive accumulation of multiple mutations in genes controlling cell growth, survival, and invasion over time": "",
  "The model that environmental hits to the body cause physical damage leading to tumors": "",
  "The theory that cancer only develops after exposure to exactly two carcinogens": "",
  "The idea that a single mutation in any gene can cause cancer immediately": "",
  "The multi-hit model states that cancer develops through the sequential accumulation of multiple mutations (hits) in oncogenes, tumor suppressors, and other genes. This explains why cancer incidence increases with age and why most cancers take years to develop.": "",
  "A pathologist examines a biopsy and finds cells with an abnormally high number of chromosomes, disorganized tissue architecture, and cells invading the basement membrane. The patient is diagnosed with cancer. Which observation most definitively distinguishes this as malignant rather than benign?": "",
  "Cells invading through the basement membrane into surrounding tissue": "",
  "The large number of dividing cells": "",
  "The abnormal chromosome number": "",
  "The disorganized tissue architecture": "",
  "Invasion through the basement membrane is the defining feature of malignancy. While benign tumors may have abnormal chromosomes and rapid division, they remain contained by the basement membrane. Penetration of this barrier indicates invasive cancer with metastatic potential.": "",
  "Hereditary retinoblastoma follows the two-hit model. Children born with one inherited mutant RB1 allele develop eye tumors at a much younger age than children with sporadic (non-inherited) retinoblastoma. Why?": "",
  "Sporadic retinoblastoma is caused by a completely different gene": "",
  "Children with one inherited mutant allele need only one additional somatic mutation (second hit) to lose all RB1 function, while sporadic cases need two somatic mutations in the same cell": "",
  "The inherited mutation activates an oncogene rather than inactivating a tumor suppressor": "",
  "Inherited cases need mutations in more genes than sporadic cases": "",
  "In hereditary retinoblastoma, every cell already carries one defective RB1 allele. Only one additional somatic mutation in any retinal cell is needed to eliminate RB1 function. In sporadic cases, both alleles must be independently mutated in the same cell, which is a much rarer event.": "",
  "HPV (Human Papillomavirus) causes cervical cancer through the action of two viral proteins: E6 and E7. E6 targets p53 for degradation, and E7 inactivates Rb. Why is targeting both of these proteins particularly effective at promoting cancer?": "",
  "E6 and E7 work together to enhance DNA repair, since the relevant cancer factors typically produce this outcome in practice": "",
  "E6 and E7 only affect immune cells, preventing tumor detection, at least according to standard theory": "",
  "E6 activates growth factor receptors while E7 promotes angiogenesis without accounting for additional influences": "",
  "E6 eliminates the DNA damage checkpoint (by degrading p53) while E7 releases the cell cycle brake (by inactivating Rb), simultaneously removing two major tumor suppressor pathways": "",
  "p53 and Rb are two of the most critical tumor suppressors. By simultaneously disabling both, HPV removes the G1 checkpoint (Rb pathway) and the DNA damage response (p53 pathway), allowing infected cells to proliferate uncontrollably with accumulated mutations.": "",
  "A colorectal cancer researcher identifies the sequence of mutations in a tumor's progression from normal colon epithelium to invasive cancer: first APC loss, then KRAS activation, then p53 loss, then additional mutations. This progression illustrates which concept?": "",
  "Colorectal cancer is entirely preventable through lifestyle changes": "",
  "All cancers follow the exact same mutational sequence": "",
  "The multi-step model of carcinogenesis, where sequential mutations in specific genes progressively transform normal tissue into cancer": "",
  "Cancer is caused by a single driver mutation": "",
  "This describes the Vogelstein model of colorectal cancer progression. Each mutation provides a selective growth advantage, and the stepwise accumulation transforms normal epithelium through adenoma stages to carcinoma. While the specific genes may vary, the multi-step principle applies to most cancers.": "",
  "Immunotherapy drugs called checkpoint inhibitors (like anti-PD-1 antibodies) have revolutionized cancer treatment. Cancer cells often express PD-L1, which binds to PD-1 on T cells and suppresses the immune response. How do checkpoint inhibitors work?": "",
  "They activate the p53 pathway in cancer cells, at least according to standard theory": "",
  "They inhibit angiogenesis to starve the tumor without accounting for additional influences": "",
  "They directly kill cancer cells by targeting their DNA, as conventional cells theory would suggest": "",
  "They block the PD-1/PD-L1 interaction, preventing cancer cells from suppressing T cell activity and allowing the immune system to attack the tumor": "",
  "Checkpoint inhibitors are antibodies that block inhibitory receptors (like PD-1) on T cells or their ligands (PD-L1) on tumor cells. By removing this immune brake, they re-enable the patient's immune system to recognize and kill cancer cells.": "",
  "A patient's tumor biopsy reveals that the tumor cells have reactivated telomerase. Why is telomerase reactivation important for tumor progression?": "",
  "Telomerase promotes angiogenesis in tumors": "",
  "Telomerase maintains telomere length, allowing cancer cells to divide indefinitely without triggering senescence": "",
  "Telomerase directly repairs cancer-causing mutations": "",
  "Telomerase enables cancer cells to metastasize": "",
  "Normal somatic cells have limited divisions because telomeres shorten with each division. Cancer cells overcome this limit by reactivating telomerase (in ~85-90% of cancers), maintaining telomere length and enabling unlimited replicative potential, one of the hallmarks of cancer.": "",
  "A family carries a BRCA1 mutation. The genetic counselor explains that family members have a significantly elevated risk of breast and ovarian cancer. A patient asks why this mutation specifically affects breast and ovarian tissues rather than all tissues. What is the best current explanation?": "",
  "BRCA1 mutations are only inherited by breast and ovarian cells": "",
  "BRCA1 is only expressed in breast and ovarian cells": "",
  "Breast and ovarian tissues undergo rapid hormone-driven proliferation, making them more dependent on BRCA1-mediated DNA repair and more vulnerable when it is compromised": "",
  "Other tissues have completely different DNA repair mechanisms": "",
  "BRCA1 is expressed in all cells and involved in homologous recombination repair. However, breast and ovarian cells undergo rapid estrogen-driven proliferation, making them particularly dependent on efficient DNA repair. When BRCA1 is defective, these rapidly dividing cells accumulate mutations faster.": "",
  "A cancer genomics study sequences 500 tumors and finds that while each tumor has thousands of mutations, only a handful of 'driver' mutations are shared across many patients. Most mutations are unique to individual tumors. What are these unique mutations called, and why are they present?": "",
  "Driver mutations; they directly cause the cancer": "",
  "Germline mutations; they were inherited from parents": "",
  "Passenger mutations; they accumulate during the rapid cell division of cancer but do not contribute to cancer development": "",
  "Beneficial mutations; they help the cancer cells survive": "",
  "Passenger mutations are incidental mutations that accumulate in cancer cells due to genomic instability and rapid division but do not contribute to cancer progression. Driver mutations are the critical mutations that directly confer a selective growth advantage.": "",
  "Liquid biopsies detect circulating tumor DNA (ctDNA) shed by cancer cells into the bloodstream. A patient's liquid biopsy shows a new KRAS mutation that was not present in the original tumor biopsy taken a year ago. What does this suggest about the tumor?": "",
  "The original biopsy was incorrectly analyzed": "",
  "The KRAS mutation came from normal cells, not the tumor": "",
  "The patient has developed a completely new cancer at a different site": "",
  "The tumor has evolved and a new clone with the KRAS mutation has emerged, possibly conferring resistance to therapy": "",
  "Tumors are heterogeneous and evolve over time through clonal evolution. Under selective pressure (often from treatment), new mutations arise in subclones that may confer growth advantages or drug resistance. The appearance of a new KRAS mutation suggests clonal evolution, possibly driving resistance.": "",
  "A research team develops a cancer vaccine that trains the immune system to recognize a neoantigen, a mutant protein unique to the patient's tumor. Why might neoantigens be effective vaccine targets compared to normal self-proteins?": "",
  "Neoantigens prevent angiogenesis in the tumor": "",
  "Neoantigens block checkpoint inhibitors from working": "",
  "Neoantigens are present on all cells, making immune targeting easy": "",
  "Neoantigens are unique to cancer cells and not found on normal tissues, so the immune response would specifically target tumor cells while sparing healthy tissue": "",
  "Neoantigens arise from somatic mutations exclusive to the tumor. Because they are not found on normal cells, the immune system has not been tolerized to them, and a vaccine targeting neoantigens can elicit a strong, tumor-specific immune response with minimal autoimmune side effects.": ""
}